[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626847&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837784626847&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

In the past the Internet had a policy that traffic not originating
or terminating at an Internet site wasn't to be transported over
the Internet as an intermediate transport mechanism.

With the advent of real domain names for sites not on or gatewayed
with the Internet proper, does this policy still hold or did it
die a silent death since it is hard to tell a UUCP site with a
domain name from a real Internet site ??

If the answer is that domain-name mail _can_ be transported over
the Internet, shouldn't the UUCP map folks be trying to eliminate
the domain-named sites from the maps and instead funneling 
traffic through Internet/UUCP gateways ??

Follow-ups are directed to comp.mail.misc.

